\par \par The group names should be meaningful and human-readable.  Examples:\par "Window Positions" - Stores the saved frames of windows.\par "Toolbars" - Stores the custom toolbar configurations.\par "Accounts" - Stores the account list and generic account options.\par \par There is nothing wrong with spreading a single plugin's preferences across multiple groups.  Nor is there anything wrong with storing the preferences of multiple plugins in a single group.   The goal is to keep things simple and logical.\par \par \par }{\f5\fs24\cf13 Keys:\par }{\f5\fs24 The individual preferences are stored by key within their groups.\par \par Since keys are never seen by the user, they can be as cryptic as desired.  However, try your best to make keys describe what is being stored.  Examples:\par "message_send_onEnter"\par "message_incoming_darkPrefixColor"\par \par \par }{\b\f5\fs24\cf13 Register the default values}{\b\f5\fs24\cf13 \par }{\f5\fs24 Before using any preferences, you must register the default values with Adium.  This should be done during init with the method:\par \par - (void)registerDefaults:(NSDictionary *)defaultDict forGroup:(NSString *)groupName;\par \par where defualtDict is a dictionary containing default values for every key you will be storing, and groupName is the desired group.\par }{\f5\fs24 \par \par }{\b\f5\fs24\cf13 Context specific preferences\par }{\f5\fs24 An interesting and powerful feature of AIPreference controller is it's ability to save preferences in a context specific way.  If the use of a preference is associated with a specific contactHandle (or group), then it can be stored in context.  }{\f5\fs24 Using this, a general preference can be set, and then overridden for an entire group or on a contact by contact basis!\par }{\f5\fs24 \par When retrieving keys, the preference controller will search in the following order:\par Handle Specific -> Group Specific -> General -> Default\par \par To store and retrieve context specific }{\f5\fs24 preference}{\f5\fs24 s, use:\par - (void)setPreference:(id)value forKey:(NSString *)inKey group:(NSString *)groupName object:(AIContactObject *)object;\par \par - (id)preferenceForKey:(NSString *)inKey group:(NSString *)groupName object:(AIContactObject *)object;\par \par \par }{\b\f5\fs24\cf13 Regular}{\b\f5\fs24\cf13  preferences\par }{\f5\fs24 If a preference is not context specific, store it using:\par \par - (void)setPreference:(id)value forKey:(NSString *)inKey group:(NSString *)groupName;\par \par - (NSDictionary *)preferencesForGroup:(NSString *)groupName;\par Regular preferences are retrieved by group.  A dictionary of all preferences in the group is returned, from which individual keys can be accessed.\par \par \par }{\b\f5\fs24\cf13 Adding preference views}{\f5\fs24 \par }\pard\plain \fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\tx960\tx1920\tx2880\tx3840\tx4800\tx5760\tx6720\tx7680\tx8640\tx9600\tx10560\tx11520\tx12480\tx13440\tx14400\tx15360\tx16320\tx17280\tx18240\tx19200\tx20160\tx21120\tx22080\tx23040\tx24000\tx24960\tx25920\tx26880\tx27840\tx28800\tx29760\tx30720\tx31680\faauto\rin0\lin480\itap0 \f4\lang1033\cgrid {\f5\cf1 - (}{\f5\cf17 void}{\f5\cf1 )addPreferenceView:(AIPreferenceViewController *)inView;\par \par }\pard\plain \s15\nowidctlpar\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx3060\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f153\fs28\lang1033\cgrid {\b\f5\fs24\cf13 Manually opening the preference window\par }\pard\plain \nowidctlpar\tx960\tx1920\tx2880\tx3840\tx4800\tx5760\tx6720\tx7680\tx8640\tx9600\tx10560\tx11520\tx12480\tx13440\tx14400\tx15360\tx16320\tx17280\tx18240\tx19200\tx20160\tx21120\tx22080\tx23040\tx24000\tx24960\tx25920\tx26880\tx27840\tx28800\tx29760\tx30720\tx31680\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\lang1033\cgrid {\f5\cf1 - (}{\f5\cf17 IBAction}{\f5\cf1 )showPreferenceWindow:(}{\f5\cf17 id}{\f5\cf1 )sender;\par }\pard \fi-480\li480\nowidctlpar\tx960\tx1920\tx2880\tx3840\tx4800\